<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-281-130  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 281 130.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 11 1989 n1163 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Broadband plans are sent to market. (proposed nationalized fibernetwork)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kaye, Jon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Both the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) and the Office ofTelecommunications (Oftel) oppose a nationalized broadband fiberoptic network, which is estimated to cost $20 billion poundssterling.andP;  Both called for a market-led solution, and a DTI reportsaid there was no obvious demand for a national fiber network.andO;Both Labor and the Social and Liberal Democrats support thenationalization plan.andP;  British Telecommunications PLC (BT) alsoopposes nationalization, saying most services can be supplied byexisting copper cabling.andP;  BT states that high definition video andhigh-speed color facsimile transmission are some of the onlyservices that require fiber optics.andP;  Oftel regulations, however,forbid BT from transmitting television signals and otherentertainment-based services.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PolicyBroadbandFiber OpticsTelecommunicationsGreat Britain. Office of TelecommunicationsGovernment AgencyGreat Britain. Department of Trade and Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>